Note that it would be appropriate to look for autodefs
using [[[ -x $newfilter ]]],
but that stupid DEC Ultrix doesn't support [[test -x]], so the best I can
do in a portable way is [[test -r]].
<<first pass {\tt noweave} options>>=
-autodefs) newfilter="$LIB/autodefs.$2"
           if [ -r $newfilter ]; then <<append [[$newfilter]] to the pipeline>>
           else echo "$0: don't know how to find definitions for '$2'" 1>&2; exit 1
           fi
	   shift
           ;;
-showautodefs) <<print all legal [[-autodefs]] or complain>>; exit 1 ;;
-autolang) autolang="$LIB/autolang" ;;
-langrule) autolang="${autolang:-$LIB/autolang}"
           autolangargs="$autolangargs 're:$2'"
           shift ;;
@
The annotations must be in the stream before the autodefs filters
read it, but the autodefs filters are appended during the first pass,
before any [[-filter]] of the second pass.  [[-autolang]] is therefore
a first-pass option, and once the first pass is done the annotator is
prepended to the front of the pipeline so it runs first, wherever the
option appeared on the command line.

[[-langrule]] both turns the annotator on and hands it a
[[re:regex=lexer]] rule, the form [[autolang]] uses to classify a
chunk whose name is not a filename (see [[nowebfilters]](7)).  Each
rule keeps its own single quotes because the assembled pipeline is
run through a single [[eval]]: the quotes survive that
re-tokenization, so a rule reaches [[autolang]] as one argument even
when its regex contains spaces.  The only casualty is a regex
containing a single quote, which this scheme cannot carry---an
acceptable limit, as patterns over chunk names have no use for one.
<<insert autolang ahead of the autodefs filters>>=
if [ -n "$autolang" ]; then
  if [ -n "$using_index" ]; then
    <<discover languages and add their autodefs filters>>
  fi
  filters="$autolang$autolangargs$nl$filters"
fi
@
Annotating the stream is only half of what [[-autolang]] can do: it
also knows enough to choose the autodefs filters itself, so that a
plain [[noweave -autolang -index]] indexes every language present
without the user naming each one with [[-autodefs]].  The obstacle is
timing.  The pipeline is fixed before any markup flows, yet the
languages are not known until the inference has read the whole
stream---a filter cannot add filters behind itself.  The only way out
is to run the inference once \emph{ahead} of the real pipeline, purely
to learn the language set; that is what [[autolang -list]] is for
(see [[tominted.nw]]).

We restrict this to weaves that index ([[using_index]]): an autodefs
filter exists to feed [[finduses]]/[[noidx]], so without [[-index]]
its [[@index]] lines have no consumer and would only litter the
output.  Adding \emph{every} installed filter instead of just the
discovered ones would be wrong, not merely wasteful: a chunk the
inference cannot classify carries no [[@language]], and an autodefs
filter skips only chunks whose language is known and foreign, so an
unclassified chunk would be scanned by all of them and salt the index
with definitions read under the wrong grammar.  Discovery adds
exactly the filters a careful user would have typed.

The pre-pass buffers [[markup]]'s output to a temporary file rather
than running [[markup]] twice, because with no file arguments
[[markup]] reads standard input, which a first pass would consume and
leave empty for the second.  The same file then feeds the real run
(see [[<<emit raw markup>>]]), so [[markup]] still parses the source
just once.  Because that one parse now feeds \emph{both} the
discovery and the weave, a [[markup]] that fails---malformed input,
say---must stop the run rather than let an empty or truncated cache
become a confidently empty weave; its exit status is checked for
exactly that.  The list is read through [[eval]] for the same reason the
whole pipeline is: a [[-langrule]] rule sits in [[autolangargs]]
wrapped in single quotes, and only [[eval]] strips them so the rule
reaches [[autolang]] as one argument.  A language with no installed
[[autodefs.$lang]] is dropped by the [[test -r]], which is how
languages we cannot index---and the [[text]] of prose chunks---fall
away silently.

A discovered filter must not be added when the pipeline already holds
it, or identifiers in that language would be indexed twice.  Equal
filenames are not a strong enough test: the autodefs filters are
installed under several names that are byte-for-byte copies of one
program---[[autodefs.bash]] is [[autodefs.sh]], [[autodefs.python]]
is [[autodefs.python3]] (see [[icon/Makefile]])---and the names
[[autolang]] emits are exactly these aliases, so [[-autolang]]'s
discovered [[autodefs.python]] would otherwise stack on a
hand-written [[-autodefs python3]] and double the Python entries.
We therefore deduplicate by content: a candidate is skipped if
[[cmp]] finds it identical to any autodefs filter already in the
pipeline.  At this point---between the two option passes---the only
filters present are the first-pass [[-autodefs]] ones, so the scan
compares against exactly the hand-written filters it must not
duplicate.
<<discover languages and add their autodefs filters>>=
markupcache=`mktemp "${TMPDIR:-/tmp}/noweave.XXXXXX"` || exit 1
trap 'rm -f "$markupcache"' 0 1 2 15
$markup $markopts $arg > "$markupcache" || exit $?
for lang in `eval "$autolang$autolangargs -list" < "$markupcache"`; do
  newfilter="$LIB/autodefs.$lang"
  if [ -r "$newfilter" ]; then
    <<add [[$newfilter]] unless an identical filter is already present>>
  fi
done
@
The duplicate test walks [[$filters]] one filter per line and stops
at the first identical autodefs filter.  Lines that are not autodefs
filters (a [[-filter]] command, say) can never be a copy of one, so
the [[case]] guard skips them before [[cmp]] is reached.
<<add [[$newfilter]] unless an identical filter is already present>>=
duplicate=
oldIFS=$IFS
IFS=$nl
for f in $filters; do
  case $f in
    "$LIB/autodefs."*)
      if cmp -s "$f" "$newfilter"; then duplicate=1; break; fi ;;
  esac
done
IFS=$oldIFS
if [ -z "$duplicate" ]; then <<append [[$newfilter]] to the pipeline>>; fi
<<option printout for usage>>=
echo "-autodefs lang	Source is in language 'lang'; find definitions automatically." 1>&2
echo "-showautodefs	List languages that can be used with -autodefs" 1>&2
echo "-autolang	Annotate chunks with their language; with -index, add autodefs for each language found." 1>&2
echo "-langrule re=lang	Label chunks whose name matches regex 're' as language 'lang' (implies -autolang)." 1>&2
