A syntax-highlighted weave always needs two switches together:
[[-filter tominted]], the highlighter, and [[-option minted]], which
makes a \texttt{noweave}-generated \LaTeX\ preamble load the [[minted]]
package that [[tominted]] depends on.  [[-minted]] bundles them, so
\begin{quote}
\verb+noweave -autolang -autodefs python3 -index -minted fib.nw+
\end{quote}
suffices when \texttt{noweave} writes the preamble.  When the document
carries its own preamble (a weave with [[-delay]]) the [[minted]] option
has nothing to act on---no header is emitted---and only the filter
matters; the option does no harm there, so one spelling serves both
modes.

The first pass records the option for the header, exactly as
[[-option minted]] would:
<<first pass {\tt noweave} options>>=
-minted)  newopt="minted"; <<add [[$newopt]] to [[noweboptions]]>> ;;
@
The second pass adds the filter.  Like a bare [[-filter tominted]],
[[-minted]] must follow [[-index]] on the command line so [[tominted]]
runs last, after the index filters.
<<second pass {\tt noweave} options>>=
-minted)  newfilter="tominted"; <<append [[$newfilter]] to the pipeline>> ;;
@
<<option printout for usage>>=
echo '-minted		Shorthand for -filter tominted -option minted' 1>&2
