The pipeline is accumulated in a single variable, [[filters]], with one
filter command per line, separated by the newline held in [[nl]].  A
filter command may carry arguments and so contain spaces (for example
[[tominted -lexer noweb_lexer.py]]), but a newline never occurs inside
one, which makes the newline a safe separator and lets the list hold
arbitrarily many filters.  This is why there is no fixed number of
filter \emph{slots}: earlier versions of this script enumerated a
fixed maximum, because a portable [[/bin/sh]] has no arrays, and a
document that stacked enough [[-autodefs]] filters could exhaust them.
Appending a line has no such ceiling.

The append must stay on one source line.  Were the newline written
literally inside the quotes here, noweb would indent the continuation
line to this chunk's reference column and so splice those indentation
spaces into [[filters]]; routing the newline through [[nl]] keeps the
assignment a single line and the variable clean.
<<append [[$newfilter]] to the pipeline>>=
filters="$filters$newfilter$nl"
<<show usage>>=
echo "Usage: $0 [options] [files]" 1>&2
echo "Options recognized are:" 1>&2
<<option printout for usage>>
@
To avoid inserting any extra newlines into the output, 
I use [[@literal]]to insert headers and trailers.
The altered [[PATH]] provides a convenience to people who want to
use simple names to refer to filters in [[$LIB]].
<<emit markup on standard output>>=
(
header=
case $wrapper in
  none) ;;
  latex)  header="@header $wrapper $noweboptions" 
	  trailer="@trailer $wrapper" ;;
  *)  header="@header $wrapper$arg" 
      trailer="@trailer $wrapper" ;;
esac
if [ -n "$header" ]; then echo "$header"; fi
PATH="$PATH:$LIB" 
export PATH
<<if verbose, make noise about pipeline>>
<<if verbose, show back end>>
<<build the filter pipeline from [[filters]]>>
if [ -z "$pipeline" ]; then
  <<emit raw markup>>
else
  <<emit raw markup>> | eval "$pipeline"
fi
if [ -n "$trailer" ]; then echo $trailer; fi
)
@
When language discovery has run, it left [[markup]]'s output in
[[$markupcache]]; replaying that file is exactly the second parse the
buffer was built to avoid, so the real run reads from it instead of
invoking [[markup]] again.  With no discovery the variable is empty
and [[markup]] runs as before, including the standard-input case the
buffer would otherwise be needed for.
<<emit raw markup>>=
if [ -n "$markupcache" ]; then cat "$markupcache"; else $markup $markopts $arg; fi
@
The pipeline is assembled by joining the filter lines with the shell's
[[|]] operator.  Setting [[IFS]] to a newline makes the [[for]] loop
iterate once per filter; newline is one of the shell's whitespace
separators, so the trailing newline left by each append produces no
empty final field.  The joined string is run with a single [[eval]],
which both interprets the [[|]] operators and re-tokenizes each
filter's arguments---the same re-tokenization the old per-slot
[[eval $filtera]] performed.
<<build the filter pipeline from [[filters]]>>=
pipeline=
oldIFS=$IFS
IFS=$nl
for f in $filters; do
  if [ -z "$pipeline" ]; then
    pipeline="$f"
  else
    pipeline="$pipeline | $f"
  fi
done
IFS=$oldIFS
<<if verbose, make noise about pipeline>>=
if [ -n "$verbose" ]; then
  if [ -n "$header" -o -n "$trailer" ]; then
    parenpfx="("
    if [ -n "$header" ]; then echo "(echo $header" 1>&2; parenpfx=" "; fi
    echo "$parenpfx$markup" $markopts $arg 1>&2
    if [ -n "$trailer" ]; then echo " echo $trailer" 1>&2; fi
    echo ") |" 1>&2
  else
    echo $markup $markopts $arg '|' 1>&2
  fi
  oldIFS=$IFS
  IFS=$nl
  for f in $filters; do echo $f '|' 1>&2; done
  IFS=$oldIFS
fi
